13 I. J. No student may be assigned to a grade level based solely
14 on age or other factors that constitute social promotion.
15 J. K. For those students who have not met grade-level
16 performance based on scores for the standards for reading
17 foundations and processes and the vocabulary portions of the
18 statewide third-grade assessment administered pursuant to Section
19 1210.508 of this title, a school district may promote the student
20 for good cause only. Good-cause exemptions for promotion shall be
21 limited to the following:
22 1. English language learners who have had fewer than two (2)
23 years of instruction in an English language learner program;
24
Req. No. 14088 Page 13

1 2. Students with disabilities whose individualized education
2 program (IEP), consistent with state law, indicates that the student
3 is to be assessed with alternate achievement standards through the
4 OAAP;
5 3. Students who demonstrate an acceptable level of performance
6 on an alternative standardized reading assessment approved by the
7 State Board of Education. A student shall be provided one
8 opportunity during the school year and one opportunity during the
9 summer pursuant to the provisions of Section 1210.508E of this title
10 to demonstrate an acceptable level of performance on an alternative
11 standardized reading assessment;
12 4. Students with disabilities who participate in the statewide
13 assessments administered pursuant to Section 1210.508 of this title
14 and who have an IEP that reflects that the students have received
15 intensive remediation in reading and have made adequate progress in
16 reading pursuant to the student’s IEP; and
17 5. Students who have received intensive remediation in reading
18 through a program of reading instruction for two (2) or more years
19 but still demonstrate a deficiency in reading and who were
20 previously retained in third grade.
21 L. 1. To request a good-cause exemption as provided for in
22 subsection K of this section, a third-grade student’s teacher shall
23 submit documentation to the school principal that indicates the
24 promotion of the student is appropriate and is based on the
Req. No. 14088 Page 14

1 stud ent’s record. The documentation shall consist of the specific
2 good-cause exemption being requested and shall clearly prove that
3 the student is eligible for the exemption.
4 2. The principal shall review and discuss the recommendation
5 with the teacher and the third-grade student’s parent(s) or legal
6 guardian(s) and shall make a recommendation in writing to the school
7 district superintendent as to whether the student shall be promoted.
8 3. After review, the school district superintendent shall
9 accept or reject the recommendation of the principal in writing.
10 4. The parent(s) or legal guardian(s) of a third-grade student
11 who is eligible for a good-cause exemption may choose that the
12 student be retained for one (1) year even if the school district
13 superintendent accepts a recommendation for a good-cause exemption
14 pursuant to this subsection.
15 M. Third-grade students who are subject to retention pursuant
16 to the provisions of this section shall receive a minimum of ninety
17 (90) minutes each school day of scientifically research-based
18 intensive intervention services that include instruction in
19 phonological awareness, decoding, fluency, vocabulary, and
20 comprehension and other strategies prescribed by a school district
21 which may include, but are not limited to:
22 1. Small group instruction;
23 2. Reduced teacher-to-student ratios;
24
Req. No. 14088 Page 15

1 3. Tutoring in scientifically research-based reading services
2 in addition to the ninety (90) minutes required by this subsection;
3 4. The option of transition classes;
4 5. Extended school day, week, or year;
5 6. Summer reading academies, as provided for in Section
6 1210.508E of this title; and
7 7. Placement of the student in a classroom with a teacher rated
8 superior or highly effective in accordance with the Oklahoma Teacher
9 and Leader Effectiveness Evaluation System.
10 N. Each school district may provide an intensive acceleration
11 class for retained third-grade students. The focus of the intensive
12 acceleration class shall be to increase the reading level of a
13 student at least two grade levels in one school year. The intensive
14 acceleration class shall provide reading instruction and
15 intervention for the majority of student contact each school day and
16 incorporate opportunities to master fourth-grade subject matter
17 standards in core academic areas.
18 O. 1. The State Department of Education shall employ literacy
19 coaches to assist in implementing the provisions of this act. Each
20 literacy coach shall:
21 a. (1) hold a master’s degree in education with three
22 (3) years of documented successful experience
23 teaching reading, or
24
Req. No. 14088 Page 16

1 (2) hold a bachelor’s degree with five (5) years of
