20 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY 70 O.S. 2021, Section 1210.508D,
21 as amended by Section 6, Chapter 411, O.S.L. 2024 (70 O.S. Supp.
22 2025, Section 1210.508D), is amended to read as follows:
23 Section 1210.508D. A. Contingent on the provision of
24 appropriated funds designated for the Strong Readers Act, school
Req. No. 14088 Page 22

1 dist ricts may be allocated monies for each enrolled kindergarten
2 student or first-, second-, and third-grade student of the current
3 school year, including any student who has been retained in the
4 third grade pursuant to Section 1210.508C of this title, who is
5 found to be in need of remediation or intensive intervention
6 services in reading. The allocation shall be distributed to each
7 school district upon approval of the strong readers plan for the
8 school district by the State Board of Education and the submittal of
9 a child-count report to the State Department of Education that
10 details the number of students identified as needing remediation or
11 intensive intervention services in reading. To determine a per-
12 student allocation amount, the total amount of funds available for
13 allocation each year shall be divided by the total number of
14 students in the state identified as in need of remediation or
15 intensive intervention services in reading as provided for in
16 Section 1210.508C of this title. Each school district shall be
17 allocated an amount equal to the per-student allocation amount
18 multiplied by the number of identified students enrolled in the
19 school district.
20 B. Beginning with the 2022-2023 school year, districts
21 receiving more than Two Thousand Five Hundred Dollars ($2,500.00)
22 pursuant to subsection A of this section shall spend no less than
23 ten percent (10%) to provide professional development for teachers
24 teaching prekindergarten through grade five. The professional
Req. No. 14088 Page 23

1 deve lopment shall include training in the science of reading
2 including how students learn to read; training in providing explicit
3 and systematic instruction in phonological awareness, decoding,
4 fluency, vocabulary, and comprehension; implementing reading
5 strategies that research has shown to be successful in improving
6 reading among students with reading difficulties; and instructional
7 materials required for implementation.
8 C. By June 30, 2022, the Department shall approve and publish a
9 list of professional development programs that are evidence-based
10 and directly address the cognitive science of how students learn to
11 read for which districts are permitted to use the funds received
12 under this section.
13 D. If a teacher attends and completes a professional
14 development institute in elementary reading approved by the
15 Commission for Educational Quality and Accountability during the
16 summer or when school is not in session, the teacher may receive a
17 stipend equal to the amount of the cost for a substitute teacher,
18 based on the amount of funds allocated.
