20 as amended by Section 7, Chapter 411, O.S.L. 2024 (70 O.S. Supp.
21 2025, Section 1210.508E), is amended to read as follows:
22 Section 1210.508E. A. If a teacher determines that a student
23 in kindergarten or first through third grade is not reading at grade
24 level by the end of the second quarter of the school year, the
Req. No. 14088 Page 24

1 pare nt parent(s) or legal guardian guardian(s) of the student shall
2 be notified of:
3 1. The reading level of the student;
4 2. The program of reading instruction for the student as
5 required pursuant to the Strong Readers Act; and
6 3. The potential need for the student to participate in a
7 summer academy or other program designed to assist the student in
8 attaining grade-level reading skills.
9 B. A teacher who determines a student in kindergarten or first
10 through third grade is not meeting grade-level targets for reading
11 may shall, after consultation with the parent parent(s) or legal
12 guardian guardian(s) of the student, recommend that the student
13 participate in and complete a summer academy or other program.
14 C. Summer academy programs shall be designed to ensure that
15 participating students successfully complete grade-level
16 competencies in reading to enhance next-grade readiness. A summer
17 academy reading program shall be a program that incorporates the
18 content of a scientifically research-based professional development
19 program administered by the Commission for Educational Quality and
20 Accountability or a scientifically research-based reading program
21 administered by the State Board of Education and is taught by
22 teachers who have successfully completed professional development in
23 the reading program or who are certified as reading specialists.
24
Req. No. 14088 Page 25

1 D. School districts may approve an option for students who are
2 unable to attend a summer academy. The optional program may
3 include, but is not limited to, an approved private provider of
4 instruction, approved computer- or Internet-based instruction, or an
5 approved program of reading instruction monitored by the parent
6 parent(s) or legal guardian guardian(s). School districts shall not
7 be required to pay for the optional program but shall clearly
8 communicate to the parent parent(s) or legal guardian guardian(s)
9 the expectations of the program and any costs that may be involved.
10 E. 1. Beginning with the summer following completion of the
11 2027-2028 school year, each school district in this state shall
12 provide an in-person summer academy or other program to students
13 who:
14 a. do not meet grade-level performance based on scores
15 for the standards for reading foundations and
16 processes and the vocabulary portions of the statewide
17 third-grade assessment administered pursuant to
18 Section 1210.508 of this title, and
19 b. do not demonstrate an acceptable level of performance
20 on an alternative standardized reading assessment when
21 taken the first time during the student’s third-grade
22 year in accordance with the provisions of paragraph 3
23 of subsection K of Section 1210.508C of this title.
24
Req. No. 14088 Page 26

1 2. Students who participate in a summer academy or other
2 program pursuant to the provisions of this subsection shall be given
3 an alternative standardized reading assessment approved by the State
4 Board of Education pursuant to the provisions of paragraph 3 of
5 subsection K of Section 1210.508C of this title prior to July 1. A
6 student who demonstrates an acceptable level of performance on the
7 assessment shall be promoted to the fourth grade.
8 3. The summer academy or other program provided pursuant to
9 this subsection may be offered in cooperation with other school
10 districts or a public library or by contracting with a nonprofit
11 education organization. School districts shall notify the State
12 Department of Education by December 1, 2028, and each December 1
13 thereafter, of its plan to provide a summer academy or other
14 program.
15 F. Subject to the availability of funds, beginning one (1) year
16 after implementation of this section, the requirements of subsection
17 B of this section may be expanded to apply to students in fourth
18 grade. Each year thereafter, the requirements may be expanded by
19 one grade level until the requirements apply to third-grade students
20 through eighth-grade students. Summer academy programs shall be
21 designed for each grade level. Nothing in this section shall
22 prevent the State Board of Education or a school district board of
23 education from utilizing private, local, or federal funds to
24 implement this section.
Req. No. 14088 Page 27

1 F. G. The State Board of Education shall adopt rules to
2 implement the provisions of this section which shall include
3 requirements for instructional time for summer academy programs,
4 teacher qualifications, and evaluation of student achievement as a
5 result of summer academy programs or other optional programs.
6 SECTION 5. This act shall become effective July 1, 2026.
7 SECTION 6. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
8 of the public peace, health, or safety, an emergency is hereby
9 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
10 be in full force from and after its passage and approval.
